Using the diagnostic coding of the PSS-I as the state condition (1 = positive for PTSD, 0 = negative) and the new 3-item brief PSS-I as the test variable, we found the AUC to be .96 supporting the conclusion that the brief 3-item PSS has excellent accuracy for detecting PTSD as measured by the diagnostic version of the PSS-I (see Figure 1
). Examination of Table 2
 suggests that a cut point of 3 would be optimal for yielding high sensitivity (i.e., detecting PTSD when it is present, i.e., the true positive rate) and high specificity (i.e., not detecting PTSD when it is not present, i.e., the true negative rate). For a cut score of 3, estimated sensitivity is 94.3% with a false positive rate (i.e., 1—specificity) of 14.7% (or, conversely, a specificity of 85.3%). A cut score of “2” would raise the chance of false positives considerably (i.e., reduce specificity) and not improve sensitivity substantially. A cut score of “4” would reduce sensitivity to 88.6%.
